        {
          "question": "Can my parent get SNAP if they own their home outright?",
          "answer": "Yes. Kentucky doesn't count your parent's home as an asset for SNAP eligibility, regardless of its value. They can also keep their car and most retirement savings accounts without affecting their benefits."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my parent lives with me but we buy groceries separately?",
          "answer": "If your parent is over 60 and purchases and prepares food separately from the rest of the household, they can apply as a one-person household. This often results in higher benefits than being counted as part of a larger household."
        },
        {
          "question": "How much will my parent actually receive each month?",
          "answer": "Benefits depend on net income after deductions for medical expenses and housing costs. A typical single senior receives around $188/month, but this can be much higher if they have significant medical or housing expenses that reduce their countable income."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply for SNAP on behalf of my elderly parent?",
          "answer": "Yes, if your parent cannot apply themselves due to age or disability. You'll need to be designated as their authorized representative. Call 1-855-306-8959 to discuss the process and required documentation."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if my parent's Social Security increases next year?",
          "answer": "SNAP benefits automatically adjust when income changes. Your parent will need to report the increase within 10 days, and DCBS will recalculate their benefits. Small increases often don't eliminate benefits entirely due to medical and housing deductions."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my parent use SNAP benefits to buy groceries online?",
          "answer": "Yes, Kentucky SNAP recipients can use their EBT cards for online grocery purchases at approved retailers like Amazon, Walmart, and Kroger. They cannot use benefits for delivery fees, but can pay those separately."
        }
