      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "What if my parent's landlord won't give written permission for the weatherization work?",
          "answer": "Without landlord permission, your parent cannot receive weatherization services as a renter. The program requires landlords to sign documents granting permission before any work begins. Try explaining that the improvements increase property value at no cost to the landlord. If the landlord still refuses, your parent won't be eligible for this program."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my parent apply if their home was weatherized 20 years ago?",
          "answer": "It depends on exactly when the work was done. Homes weatherized on or after September 30, 1994 are generally ineligible. However, homes weatherized before October 1, 1993 may qualify for re-weatherization. You'll need documentation of when the previous work occurred to determine eligibility."
        },
        {
          "question": "How long will my parent really wait for weatherization services?",
          "answer": "Wait times vary significantly by region and your parent's priority level. Applications are prioritized every six months using a point system, with elderly and disabled applicants receiving higher priority. Some areas may have shorter waits, while others could take a year or more depending on funding and demand."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if my parent's income changes while they're on the waitlist?",
          "answer": "Eligibility remains valid for 12 months from the date it was verified. If 12 months pass without work beginning, your parent must re-verify their income and eligibility to continue. If income rises above the limits during this time, they may no longer qualify for services."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply on behalf of my elderly parent who has difficulty traveling to the Community Action Agency office?",
          "answer": "The program requires the applicant to reside in the home being weatherized, but the research doesn't specify whether family members can submit applications on behalf of parents. Contact your local Community Action Agency directly to ask about accommodation options for elderly or disabled applicants who have difficulty visiting the office."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my parent's income is slightly above the limit but they received K-TAP benefits last year?",
          "answer": "Your parent may still qualify through the alternative eligibility pathway. The program accepts households where any member received TANF or K-TAP cash assistance within the 12 months prior to application, regardless of current income level. Bring documentation of the K-TAP benefits when applying."
        }
      ],
