      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "Can my parent keep their house if it's worth more than $2,000?",
          "answer": "Yes, the primary home is exempt from the $2,000 asset limit if your parent intends to return to it. The home equity value doesn't count toward Medicaid asset limits. However, if they plan to live elsewhere permanently, the home may need to be sold or transferred according to Medicaid rules."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens after the 365 days of enhanced funding ends?",
          "answer": "Services continue through standard Kentucky Medicaid home and community-based waivers like ABI or HCBW, but without the extra benefits. Your parent will still receive necessary care, but may have fewer service hours or options than during the first transition year."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I hire myself or another family member as my parent's paid caregiver?",
          "answer": "Yes, through the self-direction option, you can choose services and hire caregivers including relatives. This allows family members to be compensated for providing care that would otherwise be delivered by agency staff."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my parent has been in the nursing home for less than 60 days?",
          "answer": "They don't qualify yet — the 60 consecutive days is a firm requirement. However, you can start the referral process before the 60 days are complete so everything is ready when they become eligible."
        },
        {
          "question": "Does the program cover nursing home costs if my parent needs to return to the facility?",
          "answer": "The program focuses on community transition, but your parent remains eligible for nursing home care through Kentucky Medicaid if their needs change and community services are no longer sufficient."
        },
        {
          "question": "Are there regional differences in wait times or available services?",
          "answer": "Yes, the program is administered through local contact agencies like Area Agencies on Aging, which can lead to differences in processing times and available service providers by region. Contact your local agency for area-specific information."
        }
      ],
